---
import DocsLayout from "../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
import VariantBlock from "../../../components/docs/VariantBlock.astro";
import BasicDemo from "../../../components/docs/demos/gsap-hero-01/Basic.astro";
import basicSource from "../../../components/docs/demos/gsap-hero-01/Basic.astro?raw";
---

<DocsLayout
  title="GSAP Hero 01"
  description="Full-height hero with a ScrollTrigger-scrubbed parallax background layer -- the registry's first tier-2 (GSAP) item. Ships populated, same copy-and-own convention as the tier-1 Hero family, but the background slot is a genuine continuous scroll-linked animation, not a static layer."
  registry="gsap-hero-01"
  sourceFile="sections/GsapHero-01.astro"
>
  <h2>Before you start -- this installs an npm dependency</h2>
  <ul class="docs-list">
    <li>
      <code>npx shadcn add @astro-shad/gsap-hero-01</code> installs <code>gsap@^3.13.0</code> alongside the
      component file -- same pattern as <a href="/docs/components/map">Map</a>'s <code>maplibre-gl</code>. No other
      astro-shad primitive pulls in a runtime npm package; every tier-1 item (see{' '}
      <a href="/docs/components/motion">Motion</a>) stays zero-dependency on purpose.
    </li>
    <li>
      Why GSAP, not <code>@astro-shad/motion</code>: the background layer's position is continuously tied to scroll
      offset (<code>scrollTrigger: {'{'} scrub: true {'}'}</code>), not a one-shot entrance. Tier-1's{' '}
      <code>IntersectionObserver</code>-driven triggers fire once or toggle; they don't scrub. This component
      intentionally doesn't reimplement anything the zero-dependency runtime could already do.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Preview</h2>
  <p>
    Scroll the preview area -- the oversized background layer (<code>inset-x-0 -top-[15%] -bottom-[15%]</code>)
    translates <code>yPercent -10 → 10</code> against scroll position, edges always covered at both extremes.
  </p>
  <VariantBlock registry="gsap-hero-01" source={basicSource} previewClass="p-0">
    <BasicDemo />
  </VariantBlock>

  <h2>Props</h2>
  <p>
    Same as the tier-1 heroes (frontend contract §7): no content props. Accepts <code>class</code> and arbitrary
    rest attributes. The <code>background</code> slot fallback is an Unsplash demo image + scrim -- swap the{' '}
    <code>src</code> for a local asset, or fill the slot to replace the layer entirely; the parallax mechanism lives
    on the wrapper, not the slot content, so a swapped image still animates correctly.
  </p>

  <h2>Notes</h2>
  <ul class="docs-list">
    <li>
      <strong>Scroller auto-detection.</strong> ScrollTrigger defaults to <code>window</code> as the scroll
      container, which breaks inside a nested <code>overflow-y: auto</code> preview area (like this docs page's own
      component previews, or <code>/dev</code>'s per-board scroll region). The component walks up from itself for
      the nearest scrollable ancestor and falls back to <code>window</code> when none is found -- no prop needed,
      this is automatic.
    </li>
    <li>
      <code>prefers-reduced-motion</code> skips creating the ScrollTrigger entirely -- no reduced-motion fallback
      animation, since a static hero with no parallax already reads correctly with zero extra code.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Known gap, stated honestly:</strong> ScrollTrigger instances are never explicitly <code>.kill()</code>
      'd. Harmless today -- this registry has no Astro view-transitions (<code>ClientRouter</code>) anywhere, so
      plain MPA navigation tears the whole page down between routes and there's nothing to leak. If your project (or
      a future version of this one) adopts view-transitions, add an <code>astro:before-swap</code> cleanup pass
      before relying on this component across client-side route swaps.
    </li>
    <li>
      Porting philosophy diverges from tier-1 on purpose: the script is close to stock ScrollTrigger boilerplate
      (<code>registerPlugin</code> + one <code>gsap.fromTo</code>), not funneled through a custom preset
      abstraction -- so a real GSAP snippet found elsewhere can be pasted in here with minimal translation.
    </li>
    <li>Pulls in <code>badge</code> and <code>button</code> automatically via registry dependencies.</li>
  </ul>
</DocsLayout>
